Given the lack of regulating legal provisions, the criteria for performing abortion in Bosnia and Herzegovina are not fully clear, making women believe that the termination of pregnancy is the “easy way” to resolve various problems.

Director of the non-governmental organization Green Action, Alma Čaušević, told SETimes that there have been a number of convictions that women in the country bear the highest physical and mental burden of war trauma, such as rape and crimes committed against them, a conflict they are experiencing even now.

“Along with traumatic events, particularly those related to rape and war crimes perpetrated by men of the other gender, women in Bosnia and Herzegovina are also exposed to the risks of unwanted and unplanned pregnancies, which is no doubt another consequence of trauma,” Čaušević said. “Women should have full control over their bodies and sexuality, especially after experiencing rape and war, instead of considering any obstetrical measure as the ‘easy way’ to solve their own and a family’s problems.”

She added that it is the job of the authorities to protect women’s reproductive rights.

The survival of a small number of women’s health and medical organizations is a clear sign of the lack of funds, political will and awareness about women’s sexual and reproductive rights, according to Čaušević.

Olgu Haj
